	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Safe Haven</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/steve-fellner">Steve Fellner</a></li><li><a href="/issues/361">January 2006</a></li></ul>

			</div>

																			

				<figure class="block-content-photo block-content-photo-large photo photo-outset-center-small">
					
					<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1525 1960'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/763x980r/photos/361-24-zahigian.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1525x1960r/photos/361-24-zahigian.jpg
	 alt="361 - Zahigian - Fellner"
	 class="lazy">

										<figcaption>

						
																				<div class="photo-credit">
								&copy;&nbsp;<a href="/contributors/jennifer-zahigian">Jennifer Zahigian</a>
							</div>
																		</figcaption>
									</figure>

					</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p><strong><span class="large">&ldquo;SO,</span></strong> aren&rsquo;t you going to make the offer?&rdquo; my mother said when I answered the phone.</p>

<p>I had no idea what she was talking about. &ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;re actually going to make me ask.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Again, I drew a blank.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, for God&rsquo;s sake,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Can your brother and I stay with you? We don&rsquo;t have anywhere else to go.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Of course. They were living in coastal Mississippi, and their new home was in danger of being swept away by the approaching hurricane, Katrina.</p>

<p>My younger brother Eric had recently taken a job on the Gulf Coast, keeping books for a few family-run hotels there, and my mother had come to live with him after she&rsquo;d given up on working. She was losing her vision, but her inability to hold down a job had as much to do with her attitude as with her disability. She hated the South and wasn&rsquo;t too keen on living with my brother. Still, at least he&rsquo;d made the offer.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You need to stay with me,&rdquo; I said. It was part declaration, part question.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We need to stay with <em>family</em>,&rdquo; she said.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong><span class="large">THE</span></strong> day my mother and my brother flew in, I went to pick them up at the airport. At first I&rsquo;d told them I couldn&rsquo;t be there: I had to teach a class. (Of course, as the instructor, I could easily have canceled.) My mother&rsquo;s reply was &ldquo;So help me God, if you make us get a cab, I&rsquo;ll pick up the goddamn white courtesy phone at the airport, page Mother Nature, and tell her to send Katrina to find you.&rdquo;</p>

<p>My brother trailed behind my mother at the terminal. He didn&rsquo;t look happy to see me. We hadn&rsquo;t talked since I&rsquo;d gone away to college years ago, leaving him and my mother in the trailer park in Illinois. He&rsquo;d never said as much, but I think he resented my going to college. I could tell he was proud that he&rsquo;d become an accountant and now had the money to take care of himself, and our mother as well. He liked living in Mississippi. The conservative atmosphere agreed with him, as did the offshore casinos.</p>

<p>&ldquo;How are you?&rdquo; I asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re here,&rdquo; Eric said.</p>

<p>In the car my mother kept looking warily at my brother&rsquo;s face, which made me nervous. Could she tell, even with her limited eyesight, how unhappy he was to see me?</p>

<p>&ldquo;My apartment is real small,&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s real, real small. Conditions are going to be cramped.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;We all lived together before,&rdquo; Eric said. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sure we&rsquo;ll get used to it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Is it clean?&rdquo; my mother said.</p>

<p>This was especially insulting coming from her, because she&rsquo;d never been a good housekeeper. Not that it had been her fault. After my father left, she&rsquo;d been forced to work three different jobs. No time to wax the kitchen floor and polish the light fixtures.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes and no,&rdquo; I said in response to her question.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What an answer,&rdquo; Eric said. &ldquo;If it&rsquo;s not clean, just say so. Is that what they taught you in grad school: yes and no, everything&rsquo;s relative, blah, blah, blah? They don&rsquo;t let you flit by with that shit when you get a real job.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Get along, dummies,&rdquo; my mother said. &ldquo;It doesn&rsquo;t matter whether it&rsquo;s clean. That&rsquo;s the good thing about going blind: who cares what something looks like.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong><span class="large">OVER</span></strong> dinner we drank a bottle of wine, which felt odd. When I was growing up, none of us had ever touched alcohol. It had been something that set us apart from the rest of the poor families in the trailer park &mdash; or so we&rsquo;d needed to believe. Now here we all were, drinking together.</p>

<p>The conversation hit a particularly uncomfortable lull, though we hadn&rsquo;t been talking that much to begin with.</p>

<p>&ldquo;How bad do you think things are going to get?&rdquo; I asked, thinking it might break the tension.</p>

<p>My mother reached over and pinched my hand. I felt embarrassed. I knew I had said something stupid.</p>

<p>Changing the subject, she told us that ever since she&rsquo;d lost most of her sight, the locals in Mississippi &mdash; particularly older women &mdash; treated her like an oracle. They would come up to her in restaurants or stop her in the middle of the street and ask her personal questions about their life or their future. It was the strangest thing, she said, and a little scary. Only to relative strangers could she play this role; for anyone who&rsquo;d known her for any length of time, the illusion vanished.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Sometimes I like the attention,&rdquo; my mother said.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You always have,&rdquo; my brother remarked, tapping his fork against the edge of the table.</p>

<p>My mother looked to me for support. She could always count on me to take the opposite side from my brother on any issue.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Strangely enough,&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not going to argue with him on that point.&rdquo;</p>

<p>My mother appeared shocked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;There&rsquo;s a first time for everything,&rdquo; I told her.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Congratulations to the both of you, then,&rdquo; she replied.</p>

<p>Going on with her story, she said that if she were in Mississippi now, she&rsquo;d be afraid someone might approach her and ask about the well-being of a relative, friend, or spouse. She wouldn&rsquo;t want to have to tell them she didn&rsquo;t know. &ldquo;Sometimes I think it would be better to lie,&rdquo; my mother said. &ldquo;Is there anything more cruel than to say, &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know&rsquo;?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know,&rdquo; my brother said.</p>

<p>I surprised myself by laughing at this, which made my brother laugh. Then we were all laughing, as if something truly hilarious had been said. We&rsquo;d been needing some sort of release, though I wasn&rsquo;t sure we deserved one.</p>

<p><figure class="photo photo-outset-center-medium">
	<div>
