										</a>
																	</div>
																								</figcaption>
							</div>
			</div>
</figure>
</p>

<p><strong><span class="large">THE</span></strong> next morning my mother walked into my room and stumbled over a pile of laundry. &ldquo;If I&rsquo;m aware how much of a pigsty this place is, it must be pretty bad,&rdquo; she said.</p>

<p>I didn&rsquo;t say anything. It was the only way I knew to punish her.</p>

<p>She grabbed my hand and forced me to open my palm. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m going to tell your future,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;I might as well take the role I&rsquo;ve been given and run with it: Madame Mom, the blind marvel &mdash; knows all, sees all.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I told her to go ahead. I needed something to look forward to.</p>

<p>She dropped my hand. &ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo;</p>

<p>I said nothing.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t tell me you need something to look forward to. Really. Don&rsquo;t.&rdquo; She was stunned and a little angry. &ldquo;Your family is here. We&rsquo;re together.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;That&rsquo;s one way of looking at it,&rdquo; I said.</p>

<p>Later that day my brother asked if I wanted to come outside and have a smoke.</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t smoke, but I like people who do. They always seem to have a story to tell, something on their minds, as if the cigarettes were just a distraction, a prop to keep them from focusing on their problems. My brother had started smoking in junior high. I remember the first time I saw him sharing a cigarette with friends. He looked so cool. I was jealous. As the older brother, I was supposed to be the mature, edgy one.</p>

<p>Eric and I went outside, and he offered me a cigarette. He looked disappointed when I refused.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We didn&rsquo;t have to stay with you,&rdquo; Eric said. &ldquo;I have money. We could have stayed at a hotel.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;This is a good thing,&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;I wanted for all of us to spend some time together.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Liar.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Are you scared?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;A little,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want anything to happen to my house. I worked hard for that house.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He had worked hard. It was a real house: two stories, garage, attic, shutters. For the first time I was aware how important owning a home was. It embarrassed me that I&rsquo;d never thought of this before.</p>

<p>&ldquo;A house is a good thing,&rdquo; I said. It felt like a stupid comment. &ldquo;Do you think I&rsquo;m dumb for saying that?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Of course not,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I was thinking the same thing. Plus, you&rsquo;re my older brother. You can&rsquo;t be too stupid &mdash; even if you are an overeducated shithead.&rdquo;</p>

<p>My mother came outside. My brother dropped his cigarette and squashed it with his foot.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve lost my vision,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;not my sense of smell.&rdquo; Then she added: &ldquo;Give me a cigarette.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You sure?&rdquo; my brother asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s been a long couple of days,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Give me a goddamn cigarette.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong><span class="large">LATER</span></strong> that night the three of us were sitting around watching <span class="smallcaps">TV</span>. We couldn&rsquo;t watch the news of the hurricane, because it made Eric and my mom too nervous. So we settled on a thriller on the Lifetime channel: the heroine was unknowingly married to a serial killer who&rsquo;d had plastic surgery to make him look exactly like her husband, whom he&rsquo;d secretly killed. My mother was so involved in the plot she couldn&rsquo;t sit still. She kept gasping and saying, &ldquo;Oh my God,&rdquo; over and over again. I didn&rsquo;t understand how such a mediocre movie could affect her so. She couldn&rsquo;t even see the screen.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What&rsquo;s your problem?&rdquo; my brother said to my mother.</p>

<p>I immediately felt bad. How could we deny our mother this small pleasure?</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m watching the movie,&rdquo; my mother said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s pretty intense.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m watching the movie, too,&rdquo; my brother said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s pretty idiotic.&rdquo;</p>

<p>My mother picked up the remote and turned off the sound.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Close your eyes,&rdquo; she said to Eric. Then she turned to me and said, &ldquo;You, too.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;OK,&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;They&rsquo;re closed.&rdquo; I hadn&rsquo;t closed my eyes. I wasn&rsquo;t going to play any of her games.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m no fool,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Some people even think I have mystical powers. You&rsquo;d better shut those eyes.&rdquo;</p>

<p>How could I ignore the command of someone with mystical powers? I shut my eyes.</p>

<p>The room was silent all of a sudden. Everything else dropped away. If I didn&rsquo;t let myself breathe, I could hear the wind outside: a low sound, like the faint echo of someone calling for help. I started to feel scared. I wanted to open my eyes, but I didn&rsquo;t. My mother couldn&rsquo;t see anything, and I wanted to be with her in the darkness. I needed to be with her.</p>

<p>I reached over and held her hand. I felt ridiculous, a grown man holding his blind mother&rsquo;s hand as they sat in a silent room with their eyes closed. This is what my life had become. I opened my eyes, just for a second, and saw my brother holding my mother&rsquo;s other hand.</p>

<p>I took a deep breath and tightened my grip.</p>
														</div>


				
